<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" ><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="4.0.0">Jekyll</generator><link href="https://srimukh.com/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><link href="https://srimukh.com/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><updated>2022-03-15T07:32:38-05:00</updated><id>https://srimukh.com/feed.xml</id><title type="html">Srimukh’s blog</title><subtitle>Notes from my explorations.</subtitle><entry><title type="html">On Emacs</title><link href="https://srimukh.com/markdown/2020/07/15/on-emacs.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="On Emacs" /><published>2020-07-15T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2020-07-15T00:00:00-05:00</updated><id>https://srimukh.com/markdown/2020/07/15/on-emacs</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://srimukh.com/markdown/2020/07/15/on-emacs.html">&lt;h1 id=&quot;insights&quot;&gt;Insights&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Control and Meta are parallels. &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;C&lt;/code&gt; acts on elementary structures like letters and symbols, but &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;M&lt;/code&gt; acts on higher level structures like words and sentences.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Three reasons why &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;C-f/b/n/p&lt;/code&gt; need to be learnt -
    &lt;ol&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;They work on all kinds of terminals&lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;These tend to be faster after practice&lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Forms basis for more advanced commands&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ol&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Some commands like &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;C-x C-l&lt;/code&gt; are disabled for beginners. Use spc to say yes.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Commands starting with &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;C-x&lt;/code&gt; mostly deal with windows, files, buffers, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Overridden behavior of keys is called being &lt;em&gt;electric&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Killed text can be yanked later. Deleted text cannot be yanked. Commands that remove a lot text generally kill it - so that it can be yanked if needed. Single character removals and space removals are deletions and cannot be yanked.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Use &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;C-x C-c&lt;/code&gt; when you need to logout&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Autosave file begins and ends with a #. To recover, &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;M-x recover-this-file &amp;lt;Ret&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Most commands do the “same job” in different modes but behave slightly differently&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;To exit recursive editing, do esc-esc-esc. &lt;code class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;C-g&lt;/code&gt; only exits current editing level.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

